---

<Base title={title} description={description} schema={schema} canonical="https://geooptimised.com/geo-audit/" ogType="article">

  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="container-wide pt-8">
    <ol class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-ink-300">
      <li><a href="/" class="transition hover:text-[var(--accent)]">Home</a></li>
      <li aria-hidden="true">/</li>
      <li><a href="/geo-monitoring/" class="transition hover:text-[var(--accent)]">GEO Monitoring</a></li>
      <li aria-hidden="true">/</li>
      <li class="text-ink-200" aria-current="page">GEO Audit</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <section class="hero-fade">
    <div class="container-wide pt-16 pb-14">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
        <span class="eyebrow">Audit Framework</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">7 June 2026</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">14 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-5 max-w-3xl font-display text-4xl font-bold leading-tight grad-text md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
        GEO Audit: Assessing AI Visibility Readiness
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-200">
        <strong class="text-white">A GEO audit systematically evaluates every signal that determines whether your brand is cited in AI-generated answers — before you invest in content or optimisation that may be built on a broken foundation.</strong> This guide explains the four dimensions every GEO audit must cover, provides a step-by-step audit framework, and includes a DIY audit table you can use immediately. For ongoing measurement after your audit, see <a href="/geo-monitoring/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO monitoring</a> and <a href="/how-to-measure-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how to measure GEO performance</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container-wide py-12 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] lg:gap-12">

    <aside class="hidden lg:block">
      <div class="sticky top-24">
        <span class="eyebrow">On this page</span>
        <nav class="toc mt-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5" id="toc-nav">
          {tocItems.map(item => (
            <a href={`#${item.id}`}>{item.label}</a>
          ))}
        </nav>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <div>

      <div class="card p-6 mb-12">
        <span class="eyebrow">Key Takeaways</span>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-200">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>A GEO audit covers four core dimensions: entity clarity, schema coverage, content extractability, and citation baseline — all four are required for an accurate AI visibility picture.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>The citation baseline must be established before any remediation work begins — it is your measurement anchor and cannot be reconstructed retrospectively.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>Technical blocks (robots.txt AI crawler exclusions) should always be fixed first — they are the fastest change and the one with the broadest downstream impact.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>Entity consistency issues are the most common root cause of poor GEO performance — and the most frequently skipped in DIY audits.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>The DIY audit table in this guide covers 14 checks across five audit areas — a pass on all 14 puts your site in the top tier of GEO readiness.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark">
        <h2 id="what-a-geo-audit-covers" class="anchor-top">What a GEO Audit Covers</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>A GEO audit is a diagnostic process that identifies every gap between your current site state and the signals AI retrieval systems require to cite your brand reliably.</strong> It does not assess keyword rankings, backlink authority, or conversion rate — those are SEO and CRO concerns. It assesses the four signals that determine AI citation: entity clarity, schema coverage, content extractability, and citation baseline.
        </p>
        <p>
          The audit is structured around a dependency chain. Technical access is the prerequisite: if AI crawlers cannot reach your content, no other optimisation matters. Entity clarity is next: AI models cite entities, not pages, so an ambiguous or inconsistently described brand will be cited less reliably than its content quality warrants. Schema coverage follows: structured data labels your content so retrieval systems can classify it correctly. Content extractability is the final layer: it determines whether individual passages are suitable for citation once the entity and technical foundations are in place.
        </p>
        <p>
          This dependency order matters for prioritisation. Brands that fix content structure before resolving entity inconsistencies see slower citation gains than those who work through the chain in order. The <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> discipline is built on this dependency model — a GEO audit makes it concrete for your specific site.
        </p>
        <p>
          The table below maps each audit dimension, what it assesses, the signals it examines, and the sources you consult to evaluate it. Use this as your audit planning reference.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border hair">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b hair bg-white/[.03]">
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Audit Dimension</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">What It Assesses</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Signals Evaluated</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Priority</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
            {auditDimensions.map(row => (
              <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">{row.dimension}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{row.what}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300 font-mono text-xs">{row.signals}</td>
                <td class={`px-4 py-3 text-xs font-semibold ${row.priority === 'Critical' ? 'text-red-300' : row.priority === 'High' ? 'text-amber-300' : 'text-ink-300'}`}>{row.priority}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="entity-clarity" class="anchor-top">Dimension 1: Entity Clarity</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Entity clarity is the audit dimension that most consistently explains the gap between content quality and citation frequency — brands with excellent content but ambiguous entities are systematically undercited.</strong> AI models retrieve and cite entities, not pages. When your brand name, category, description, and key attributes are described identically across every authoritative source the model consults, it can confidently attribute answers to you. When those descriptions diverge — even slightly — the model hedges, deprioritises, or cites a competitor whose entity is better resolved.
        </p>
        <p>
          The entity audit compares five source types: your own website (specifically your Organization schema and homepage copy), your Google Business Profile, your Wikidata entry, your LinkedIn company page, and any industry directory or publication listings. For each, extract the following attributes: brand name (exact string), primary category descriptor, founding date, location, website URL, and primary service description. Build a comparison matrix. Any cell that differs from the others is an entity inconsistency requiring correction.
        </p>
        <p>
          Pay particular attention to category descriptors. A brand that describes itself as a "digital marketing agency" on its website, a "marketing consultancy" on LinkedIn, and a "technology company" on Wikidata sends contradictory signals about what it does. AI models that cannot confidently categorise your brand may cite you less or describe you inaccurately. Aligning these descriptors is often a one-to-two day task with outsized citation impact.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="schema-coverage" class="anchor-top">Dimension 2: Schema Coverage</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Schema markup is the primary structured signal that labels your content as an attributable, authoritative source rather than an anonymous document — and most sites have significant schema gaps even when they believe their implementation is complete.</strong> A schema coverage audit checks three things: whether the correct schema types are present on each page type, whether each schema instance contains all required properties, and whether the schema validates without errors.
        </p>
        <p>
          The schema types with the greatest GEO impact are: Article or TechArticle on every content page (with headline, author, publisher, datePublished, dateModified, image, and mainEntityOfPage); FAQPage on every page with a FAQ section; BreadcrumbList on all non-homepage pages; and Organization on the homepage with sameAs linking to authoritative third-party identifiers. HowTo schema applies to procedural guides. Each of these types maps to a distinct query pattern that AI retrieval systems use to classify content.
        </p>
        <p>
          A common schema gap is deploying Article schema without the author and publisher properties referencing your Organisation. This produces an attributed document but breaks the entity link between the content and the entity that published it. Always reference the Organisation by its <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent-300">@id</code> rather than inlining a duplicate definition — this is both more efficient and structurally correct for entity graph resolution.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="content-extractability" class="anchor-top">Dimension 3: Content Extractability</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Content extractability determines whether AI systems can cleanly pull a relevant passage from your page and use it as a citation — it is the difference between content that is indexed and content that is actually quoted.</strong> Extraction-first writing has five properties: a definitional opening sentence, single-point paragraphs of two to four sentences, declarative H2/H3 headings, FAQ sections with standalone answers, and tables for comparative data. A page that satisfies all five is highly extractable. A page that satisfies none will rarely be cited even if it ranks well.
        </p>
        <p>
          The content extractability audit is a manual process on priority pages. Read the first sentence of each page. If it does not answer the primary query directly — without preamble, rhetorical questions, or context-building — the page fails the extraction test. Then scan the body: count the sentences per paragraph and flag any that exceed four. Check that H2s state the section's claim rather than asking a question. Verify the FAQ section exists and that each answer is a complete, standalone response.
        </p>
        <p>
          Retrofitting extraction-first writing to existing content is the most labour-intensive stage of a GEO audit remediation, but it is also where the citation gains are most visible. Prioritise your highest-traffic pages and your pages targeting the queries where you want to earn citations most urgently. For the full content framework, see the <a href="/geo-checklist/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO checklist</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="citation-baseline" class="anchor-top">Dimension 4: Citation Baseline</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>The citation baseline is the empirical record of your current AI visibility — it documents exactly how often, on which platforms, and with what accuracy your brand appears in AI-generated responses before any optimisation work begins.</strong> Without a baseline, you cannot measure whether your GEO programme is producing results. Establishing the baseline is the first thing a GEO audit does and the last thing you should attempt to reconstruct from memory after the fact.
        </p>
        <p>
          To establish your citation baseline, select 10–15 queries that represent the topics and categories you want to be cited in. Run each query on ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google Gemini, Microsoft Copilot, and Google AI Overviews. For each platform and query, record: whether your brand is cited, the exact text of any brand description given, whether any description is accurate, and which competitors are cited in the same response. Store this in a spreadsheet with a timestamp — you will re-run the same query set monthly to track citation frequency change.
        </p>
        <p>
          The citation baseline also reveals platform-specific performance patterns. Many brands find they perform well in Perplexity (which is heavily RAG-driven and favours well-structured, crawlable content) but poorly in Google AI Overviews (which requires stronger organic authority signals). These patterns guide where to focus remediation effort first. For the ongoing measurement framework that follows your initial audit, see <a href="/how-to-measure-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how to measure GEO</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="step-by-step-framework" class="anchor-top">Step-by-Step GEO Audit Framework</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>The six-step GEO audit framework below sequences every assessment task in dependency order — completing them out of order produces an incomplete picture and a misprioritised remediation backlog.</strong> Each step builds on the previous: you cannot meaningfully assess content extractability until you know whether crawlers can reach the content (step five) and whether schema correctly labels it (step three).
        </p>
      </div>

      <ol class="mt-8 space-y-6">
        {stepByStep.map(s => (
          <li class="flex gap-5">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border hair font-display text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)]">
              {s.step}
            </span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-white">{s.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">{s.detail}</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="diy-audit-table" class="anchor-top">DIY GEO Audit Table</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>The table below provides 14 discrete checks across five audit areas — each with a clear pass and fail definition so you can conduct a self-assessment without specialist tooling.</strong> This is an illustrative framework based on the signals that most commonly determine AI citation readiness; it is not exhaustive but covers the highest-impact checks for the majority of sites. Work through each row in order: the checks are sequenced by dependency within each area.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border hair">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b hair bg-white/[.03]">
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Area</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Check</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Pass</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Fail</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Priority</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
            {diyAuditRows.map(row => (
              <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] text-xs">{row.area}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">{row.check}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300 text-xs">{row.pass}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300 text-xs">{row.fail}</td>
                <td class={`px-4 py-3 text-xs font-semibold ${row.priority === 'Critical' ? 'text-red-300' : row.priority === 'High' ? 'text-amber-300' : 'text-ink-300'}`}>{row.priority}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
        <p>
          A site that passes all 14 checks is in strong GEO readiness. A site with three or more Critical or High failures should treat remediation as urgent — each failure compounds the others. Use the audit findings to populate a remediation backlog, and refer to the <a href="/geo-checklist/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO checklist</a> for task-level implementation guidance. To translate your audit findings into a single composite readiness score, see <a href="/geo-scoring/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO scoring</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you would like a professional audit conducted against a broader set of checks — including platform-specific citation analysis and competitor entity benchmarking — the <a href="/contact/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEOoptimised audit service</a> delivers this as a standalone engagement with a prioritised remediation plan and 90-day implementation roadmap.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="faq" class="anchor-top">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-2" id="faq-accordion">
        {faqs.map(faq => (
          <div class="card overflow-hidden">
            <button
              type="button"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between p-5 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-white transition hover:bg-white/[.02]"
              aria-expanded="false"
            >
              <span>{faq.q}</span>
              <span class="faq-icon ml-4 shrink-0 text-[var(--accent)] transition-transform duration-200">+</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body max-h-0 overflow-hidden transition-[max-height] duration-300 ease-in-out">
              <p class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">{faq.a}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <div class="mt-16" id="related">
        <span class="eyebrow">Related reading</span>
        <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
          {related.map(item => (
            <a href={item.href} class="card card-hover block p-5 no-underline">
              <span class="eyebrow">{item.tag}</span>
              <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-base font-semibold text-white">{item.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300">{item.excerpt}</p>
              <span class="mt-3 inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-[var(--accent)]">Read article <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="relative border-t hair mt-12 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="dot-grid absolute inset-0 opacity-40" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="container-wide relative py-20 text-center">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold grad-text md:text-4xl">Get a Professional GEO Audit</h2>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-5 max-w-xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">
        We conduct the complete GEO audit — citation baseline across five platforms, entity consistency matrix, schema coverage review, and content extractability scorecard — delivered as a prioritised remediation plan with a 90-day implementation roadmap.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-col items-center gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:justify-center">
        <a href="/contact/" class="btn btn-primary">Book a GEO audit</a>
        <a href="/geo-monitoring/" class="btn btn-ghost">Explore GEO monitoring</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    const faqBtns = document.querySelectorAll('#faq-accordion button');
    faqBtns.forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const body = btn.nextElementSibling as HTMLElement;
        const icon = btn.querySelector('.faq-icon') as HTMLElement;
        const open = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
        btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!open));
        if (open) {
          body.style.maxHeight = '0';
          icon.style.transform = 'rotate(0deg)';
        } else {
          body.style.maxHeight = body.scrollHeight + 'px';
          icon.style.transform = 'rotate(45deg)';
        }
      });
    });

    const tocLinks = document.querySelectorAll('#toc-nav a');
    const headings = Array.from(
      document.querySelectorAll('h2[id], h3[id]')
    ) as HTMLElement[];

    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      entries => {
        entries.forEach(entry => {
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            tocLinks.forEach(link => {
              link.classList.remove('text-[var(--accent)]');
              if (link.getAttribute('href') === '#' + entry.target.id) {
                link.classList.add('text-[var(--accent)]');
              }
            });
          }
        });
      },
      { rootMargin: '-20% 0px -70% 0px', threshold: 0 }
    );

    headings.forEach(h => observer.observe(h));
  </script>

</Base>
